She went back to Th*m*s Cook because they were better employers. Th*m*s Cook! All this is my way of saying- you can't run a charity like this. This wasn't STC's fault- it was the decisions of the company they contracted that made working their so unbearable.

The company wanted to run us as a call centre, as a business, rather than as a charity. If the mother we were speaking to only spoke Igbo and needed a translator? Too bad, that was too expensive. One of my colleagues described it as 'soul crushing' in her exit interview

Gradually, they took things away from us. We were scolded if we went to the toilet, we were marked down if our calls were too long (dealing with desperate, vulnerable people is not something you should rush if you have even an ounce of compassion) ...

It was a truly good scheme, and I loved being able to help people in real, tangible ways. The PROBLEM was that the company that held the STC contract did not have to abide by STC ethics or employee standards

I had a funding limit for each family, so I would just keep adding things until it was reached. I ordered it directly and it was delivered to their houses. Installation for electrical goods was also included

The program was amazing- vulnerable people with young children would be referred to me, I would speak to them and allocate them what they needed. Fridges, cookers, washing machines, books and children's furniture...
Before I moved to Leeds I worked for S*ve T*e Ch*ldren- except I didn't.  I worked for the company that had the STC CONTRACT. Huge difference 🧵
